Chris Mdingi, the Congress of South African Trade Unions leader in the Eastern Cape leader, has slammed President Jacob Zuma. JOHANNESBURG Chris Mdingi, the Congress of South African Trade Unions leader in the Eastern Cape leader, says President Jacob Zuma must stop asking why people have called on him to step down.He says Zuma should step down and allow Deputy President Cyril Ramaphosa to take over.Mdingi was addressing a Chris Hani memorial lecture in Uitenage in Port Elizabeth on Sunday. African National Congress (ANC) and South African Communist Party (SACP) supporters gathered at the Babs Madlakane Hall - where Ramaphosa was expected to deliver the opening address. Mdingi says ANC members are not happy with the president. The majority of our people, our constituency, have expressed their voices that we re not happy so far. We have been taught that leaders come and go but the organisation remains. (Edited by Shimoney Regter)